We can “back‐solve” the balance–sheet asset total as follows. In our books the “Initial” rows set up the opening asset balances. In our data there are three initial rows (one each for cash, bank and fixed assets) whose amounts add up to

  3000000.00 + 5000000.00 + 5000000.00 = 13 000 000.00

Then—for the period that follows—the operating transactions ultimately “transfer” value (using the double–entry system) from, say, purchases and expenses into cost of goods sold so that when sales are eventually “closed” the “profit” (plus any “other asset” items such as interest receivables) is added to the beginning amount. (For example, in our earlier sample the net effect was an increase of about 216 409.49.) 

In our new problem we may view the “flow” as follows. (A simplified method – note that in a “complete” accounting system the many purchase–and–sale lines will be balanced by, for example, the change in inventory. Here we assume that the very many “expense‐type” and “purchase‐type” transactions have already been “netted” so that effectively the net operating result is:)

  Net Operating “profit” = (Total sales – Total “cost”)
    with “cost” taken as the sum of the purchase amounts plus the fraction of expenses (including depreciation) that reduces assets.

When we sum (using the “amount” column) the many sale entries we get approximately

  Sales ≈ 5 694 115.02

The “purchase–side” entries sum to about

  Purchases ≈ 3 805 000.00

and when we add up all expenses (we include also depreciation rather than subtracting it later) we obtain

  Expenses ≈ 1 087 447.86

Thus the “cost side” is about

  3 805 000.00 + 1 087 447.86 = 4 892 447.86

so the net operating gain is roughly

  5 694 115.02 – 4 892 447.86 = 801 667.16

Moreover, several “Interest Receivable” entries (each an asset increase) when summed add roughly

  Interest ≈ 10 447.60

so that the total “net‐profit” available to boost asset values is about

  801 667.16 + 10 447.60 ≈ 812 114.76

Accordingly the ending (final) asset total is

  Initial assets (13 000 000.00) + net operating gain (≈812 114.76)
    ≈ 13 812 114.76

We present the answer rounded to two decimal places.

Thus, the answer we provide is:

------------------------------------------------
{
  "solution": {
      "Total Assets Initial Value": "13000000.00",
      "Total Assets End Value": "13812114.76"
  }
}
------------------------------------------------

This is our final answer.
